ly from Old French <i>bélier</i> ‘ram’, hence a nickname for someone thought to resemble a ram in some way or possibly a metonymic occupational name for a shepherd. In Northamptonshire the name attracts excrescent <i>-s</i> already by 1377."]}]},{"name":"Beatrix","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Late Latin personal name, which was borne by a saint martyred in Rome, together with Saints Faustinus and Simplicius, in the early 4th century. The original form of the name was probably <i>Viatrix</i>, a feminine version of <i>Viator</i> ‘voyager (through life)’, which was a favourite name among early Christians. This was then altered by association with Latin <i>Beatus</i> ‘blessed’ (<i>Via-</i> and <i>Bea-</i> sometimes being pronounced the same in Late Latin).  See also  Beatrice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Beatrix Southwell de Bellais was born in 1133, in Nottinghamshire, England as the daughter of Southwell. She had at least 1 son with Robert de Bellais. She died in 1155, in England, at the age of 22."},"et":{"1133–1155":"1133–1155","1130–1155":"1130–1155","1150–1180":"1150–1180","–Male":"Surnud","1133":"1133","1155":"1155","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1133–1155":"1133–1155","1130–1155":"1130–1155","1150–1180":"1150–1180","–Male":"Kuollut","1133":"1133","1155":"1155","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1133–1155":"1133–1155","1130–1155":"1130–1155","1150–1180":"1150–1180","–Male":"Décédé","1133":"1133","1155":"1155","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Beatrix Southwell de Bellais est née en 1133, à Nottinghamshire, Angleterre, fille de Southwell. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Robert de Be